<h2>Using Breakeven for Quick Evaluation</h2>
<p>Before doing a full EV calculation, you can quickly evaluate a trade up by asking: "Is there any realistic chance the output will be worth more than my total input cost?" If the answer is no — if every possible outcome is worth less than your total input — the trade up cannot be profitable regardless of probability distribution.</p>
<p>Conversely, if the highest-value outcome is worth much more than your inputs, the trade up might be profitable even with relatively low probability of hitting that outcome. The breakeven check helps you quickly identify which trade ups are worth analyzing in detail.</p>

<h2>Breakeven and Probability Thresholds</h2>
<p>For a trade up with a single valuable outcome and one or more low-value outcomes, you can calculate the minimum probability needed for the valuable outcome to achieve breakeven. The formula is: <strong>Min Probability = (Input Cost - Low Value × Low Prob) / (High Value - Low Value)</strong>. This tells you how many inputs must come from the high-value collection to break even.</p>

